post_text:
Greetings, ï¿¼

Last evening the Larimore School Board met in special session. All board members were present. The board approved the following:

1. Rescheduled the start of classes to August 27. We were scheduled to start on August 20. Delaying the start of the school year will give more time for teacher professional development in the area of distant learning and the use of technology in the classroom.

2. Approved in-person learning to start the school year on August 27 and give parents, who are uncomfortable in sending their children back to the school or their child has a preexisting medical condition, the option to keep their children at home for distance learning. If parents opt for distance learning it is important that those children adhere to the school schedule while they are at home.

3. Approved the Reopening Plan. This plan is considered to be somewhat fluid as there will be a need for changes as we move forward.

Have a great weekend. Stay well and safe.
Steve Swiontek, Supt.
text:
Greetings, ï¿¼

Last evening the Larimore School Board met in special session. All board members were present. The board approved the following:

1. Rescheduled the start of classes to August 27. We were scheduled to start on August 20. Delaying the start of the school year will give more time for teacher professional development in the area of distant learning and the use of technology in the classroom.

2. Approved in-person learning to start the school year on August 27 and give parents, who are uncomfortable in sending their children back to the school or their child has a preexisting medical condition, the option to keep their children at home for distance learning. If parents opt for distance learning it is important that those children adhere to the school schedule while they are at home.

3. Approved the Reopening Plan. This plan is considered to be somewhat fluid as there will be a need for changes as we move forward.

Have a great weekend. Stay well and safe.
Steve Swiontek, Supt.

Take care,
Lisa Steinbrink

post_text:
Governor Burgum has given schools permission to hold graduation exercises on or in school facilities. The Department of Public Instruction has provided guidelines for commencement ceremonies. As you may know, Mr. Triplett has developed a plan to hold Larimore High School Commencement at Lein Field on Sunday, May 24, at 2:00 PM. The ceremony involves the 25 graduates and their families in the facility, with others able to watch either from vehicles surrounding the field or watching on streamed video. The backup plan, if the weather does not permit an outdoor ceremony, is to bring the graduates to the high school gym with a limited audience. In both plans it is extremely important that everyone follows the specifics of the plan and adheres to social distancing.

After the commencement program on May 24th a Senior Graduate Parade is planned for 3:30pm. The parade route to view the Graduates will be posted around town, on the school website, and on LPS social media sites.
text:
Governor Burgum has given schools permission to hold graduation exercises on or in school facilities. The Department of Public Instruction has provided guidelines for commencement ceremonies. As you may know, Mr. Triplett has developed a plan to hold Larimore High School Commencement at Lein Field on Sunday, May 24, at 2:00 PM. The ceremony involves the 25 graduates and their families in the facility, with others able to watch either from vehicles surrounding the field or watching on streamed video. The backup plan, if the weather does not permit an outdoor ceremony, is to bring the graduates to the high school gym with a limited audience. In both plans it is extremely important that everyone follows the specifics of the plan and adheres to social distancing.

After the commencement program on May 24th a Senior Graduate Parade is planned for 3:30pm. The parade route to view the Graduates will be posted around town, on the school website, and on LPS social media sites.

Edna Ralston Library
March 30 at 1:47 PM Â·

Hello! We have heard that some parents are needing books for their children to read. We at the Edna Ralston Library are willing to help out! We are keeping our regular hours but we are only letting patrons in a few at a time. If parents want to get books for their students they are welcome to come : Mondays 5pm to 7pm, Wednesdays 1pm to 5pm and Saturdays 9am to noon. (Just knock on the door. We are limiting access.) We just ask that they come in small groups. Our catalog is online and they can message via Facebook or call the City at 701-343-2181 and we can have books prepared for them and they can be picked up curbside.

post_text:
From the Desk of the Superintendent:
March 20, 2020

Good evening everyone,

Just a couple of items tonight. We will again start with the breakfast and lunch program this coming Monday, March 23. We had over 75 students served yesterday. Please call the elementary prior to 9:00 AM to tell us how many meals you need. You may pick up those meals between 11AM and 1PM. If you do not have transportation to the elementary school, call the elementary at 343-2249 and ask if we can deliver.

We will be watching our neighbor states to see if they begin to consider sheltering in place for all residents as they have now done in New York and California.

Lastly, one of the ways that my wife and I will try to help our restaurants and the folks who work there is to order more take out. We already order take out a couple of times a week so increasing that number will not only help our hospitality people, it will also save me from cooking. Until Monday, Be Safe!

Sincerely,
Steve Swiontek, Supt.

post_text:
From the Desk of the Superintendent
For March 13, 2020

Regarding the Coronavirus (COVID 19) as it pertains to Larimore Public School. We have equipped all classrooms and school buses with Clorox wipes, and hand sanitizer. We have placed posters throughout the schools to remind students what they should do regarding all flu prevention, and reminded students to wash their hands with soap and water for at least 20 seconds several times a day. The principals and transportation director have met with their respective staffs to go over guidance for schools regarding the coronavirus provided by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC). The teachers have also prepared at-home learning resources, as well as online resources for their respective students if we are ordered to close school. We all need to stay vigilant in our prevention strategies at school, at home, and in public.

shared_text:
Larimore FFA
September 9, 2019 at 3:57 PM Â·

On Thursday, we had a very special opportunity to have a visit from Ridge Hughbanks, National Central Region VP! There are 6 National Officers serving the over 650,000 members of FFA, so we were lucky to be one of the schools visited. Ridge taught us about teamwork, failure, persistence, and community development. Our FFA Chapter is very thankful to Ridge for visiting!
